code_vulnerabilities.explanation:
The code snippet "requires login" and the message "A CSRF middleware was not detected in your express application" indicate a Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) vulnerability.

CSRF occurs when a malicious website, email, blog, instant message, or program causes a user's web browser to perform an unwanted action on a trusted site when the user is authenticated. Imagine a user is logged into their banking website. A malicious website can then use that existing authenticated session to make requests to the banking website, such as transferring funds. The banking website will believe it's the legitimate user making the request because they are already authenticated.

The vulnerability exists because the Express application lacks CSRF protection. Express, by default, does not protect against CSRF attacks. Without a CSRF protection mechanism, an attacker can craft malicious HTML or JavaScript code to send unauthorized requests to the server on behalf of an authenticated user.

To fix this, implement a CSRF protection middleware. The suggested solutions are to use `csurf` or `csrf`. These middlewares generate a unique, unpredictable token that is associated with the user's session. This token must be included in every request that modifies data. When the server receives a request, it verifies that the token in the request matches the token associated with the user's session. If the tokens don't match, the request is rejected, preventing a CSRF attack.

Implementation steps using `csurf`:

1.  Install the `csurf` package: `npm install csurf`.

2.  Import and use the middleware in your Express application:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const csrf = require('csurf');
const cookieParser = require('cookie-parser'); // csurf relies on cookie-parser

const app = express();

// Parse cookies before CSRF middleware
app.use(cookieParser());

// setup route middlewares
const csrfProtection = csrf({ cookie: true });
app.use(csrfProtection);

//Make the csrf token available in templates
app.use(function (req, res, next) {
  res.locals.csrfToken = req.csrfToken()
  next()
})

// Example route that renders a form with a CSRF token. The form would use res.locals.csrfToken in the HTML.
app.get('/form', (req, res) => {
  res.send(`
    <form action="/process" method="POST">
      <input type="hidden" name="_csrf" value="${res.locals.csrfToken}">
      <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>
  `);
});

// Route that handles the form submission (requires CSRF token validation)
app.post('/process', (req, res) => {
  // The csurf middleware already validates the CSRF token.
  res.send('Form processed successfully!');
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server listening on port 3000'));

```

The CSRF middleware now protects your application from CSRF attacks by validating the presence and correctness of the CSRF token in the requests. Make sure all forms and AJAX requests include the generated CSRF token.
